TULAREMIA - GERMANY: (RHINELAND-PALATINE) GRAPE HARVESTERS, REQUEST FOR INFORMATION
***********************************************************************************
A ProMED-mail post
http://www.promedmail.org
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
http://www.isid.org

Date: Mon 20 Nov 2016
Source: Mainz-Bingen District press release [in German, submitter SZ, edited]
http://www.mainz-bingen.de/deutsch/aktuelles_presse/pressemeldungen/20161120_hasenpest.php Six human cases of Tularemia


The health authorities of the Mainz-Bingen district [Rhineland-Palatinate] are investigating several cases of human tularemia infection. The disease can be transmitted from animals; human to human transmission is not known. The disease can be efficiently treated but cases can be severe.

All 6 patients had been harvesting grapes at the beginning of October 2016 in the northern part of the district. A couple of days later high temperature combined with a severe overall feeling of sickness was observed. The cases are unusual because infections with the pathogen (_Francisella tularensis_) are very rare in Germany and clusters of infection are even rarer.

Humans become infected through direct contact with diseased animals, their organs or excretions. The pathogen can be transmitted through contaminated food as well.

The health authorities' investigation is assisted by the state lab (LUA). The focus of the investigation is on how the patients harvesting grapes could have become infected. In addition, the federal Robert-Koch-Institut (RKI) is performing tests on samples collected from the vineyard. The focus is on food, hare/rabbit droppings, and environmental samples.

Tularemia is caused by the pathogen _F. tularensis_. The 1st signs usually are sores at the site of infection inoculation, followed by influenza-like symptoms with fever, swelling of local lymph nodes, chills, and headache. The infection can be treated with antimicrobials.

Medical practitioners in the Mainz-Bingen district are alerted and are asked to consider tularemia in patients with fever or swelling of lymph nodes, especially when the reason for symptoms cannot be established. They are required by law to notify the health authorities of suspect cases.

